The recommender system made unsuitable recommendation. 
 Its reasons are as follows: From my self-introduction the only stated preference is that I "enjoy listening to CDs very much." Because no specific genre likes or dislikes were given, I evaluated the two candidates by how well they deliver a rewarding CD listening experience based on widely known, factual attributes.
Boston (the 1976 debut, Category: Classic Rock; Album-Oriented Rock) is widely regarded as an album with exceptional studio production and an album-oriented sequence of songs. Its tightly layered electric-guitar harmonies, high production values (Tom Scholz’s multi-tracking and attention to sonic detail), and strong dynamic contrasts make it especially satisfying to listen to as a whole on a CD player or audio system. Songs such as "More Than a Feeling," "Foreplay/Long Time," and "Peace of Mind" showcase both punchy low end and clear, sustained guitar overtones — attributes that reward careful CD listening and repeatedly reveal details on repeated plays. As an AOR album it was conceived and mixed to be experienced as an album, which aligns directly with the singular preference I have for enjoying CDs as listening experiences.
Sounds of Summer: Very Best of The Beach Boys (Category: Pop; Oldies; Baroque Pop) is an excellent greatest-hits compilation that collects many of the Beach Boys’ finest singles and harmonies (e.g., "Good Vibrations," "God Only Knows," "California Girls"). It’s a superb collection for casual listening and for hearing iconic vocal arrangements and songwriting across eras. However, because it is a compilation of hits rather than a single, cohesive album crafted for continuous listening, it does not provide the same unified, album-oriented sonic journey that a dedicated CD enthusiast seeking an immersive playback experience would typically prefer. Compilations also often vary in mastering and sequencing, which can reduce the sense of a single, consistent listening experience.
Given that my only explicit preference is for enjoying CDs (and thus valuing immersive, high-fidelity album listening), Boston best matches that priority: it offers a cohesive, well-produced album experience with production and dynamics that reward attentive CD listening. For these reasons I select Boston and not the Beach Boys compilation.

